‘⁶ There are very few books,’' writes Mr. Long, ‘⁶ that are worth the trouble of reading often. Every civilized nation, however, has some such books, which have outlived the rest. A book that is to be read in all time must not be a big one. There are big books that are good in their kind, but we don’t want them for daily use. A lasting book should also treat of something that has a last- ing interest. It may be a poem, a drama, a his- tory, a biography, or other things.
